## Findings

The codebase is small and clean:
- **`src/data.ts`** — 15 mock users
- **`src/routes.ts`** — two handlers: `GET /users` (returns flat array, needs pagination) and `GET /users/:id` (fine as-is)
- **`src/types.ts`** — `User` interface with `id`, `name`, `email`, `role`
- **`tests/routes.test.ts`** — the pagination tests are **already written** using Vitest + Supertest; they're just failing because the implementation doesn't exist yet

---

## Plan: One file, one handler

**Only `src/routes.ts` needs to change.** Replace the body of the `GET /users` handler with:

```typescript
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = parseInt((req.query.page  as string) ?? "1",  10) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt((req.query.limit as string) ?? "10", 10) || 10;

  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const startIndex = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(startIndex, startIndex + limit);

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

Key design decisions:
- `|| 1` / `|| 10` fallbacks handle `NaN` from non-numeric query params
- `Array.slice` naturally returns `[]` when `startIndex >= total`, so out-of-range pages need no special case
- No new imports, no new files, no type changes needed

**Verification:** `npm test` → all 6 tests pass (4 pagination + 2 existing `/users/:id` tests).

